docs.abstract: A herd of technology public offerings this year and next year is set to anoint venture capital winners. Here are some of them.
docs.snippet: A herd of technology public offerings this year and next year is set to anoint venture capital winners. Here are some of them.
docs.lead_paragraph: Brian Chesky, chief executive of Airbnb, likes to tell the story of his early struggles to fund his home-sharing start-up. Many venture capitalists refused to meet with him, he said in an email. Some walked out in the middle of meetings.

headline.main: These Silicon Valley Investors’ Bets May Pay Off
headline.print_headline: Early Bettors Are Waiting For Rewards

docs.abstract: The offering, which is expected to be one of the biggest ever, puts the ride-hailing service neck and neck with its rival Lyft in a race to the public markets.

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Uber confidentially filed paperwork on Thursday to go public, according to two people with knowledge of the matter, officially moving toward what is expected to be one of the biggest and most anticipated tech company stock market debuts ever.

headline.main: Uber Is Said to File for an I.P.O. as It Races Lyft to a Public Debut
headline.print_headline: Uber Is Said  To Submit For an I.P.O. Next Year

docs.lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? Erin Griffith, a start-ups and venture capital reporter in San Francisco, discussed the tech she’s using.

docs.abstract: With so many start-ups listing their shares this year, each is trying to avoid the traffic jam to get its own moment in the sun.
docs.snippet: With so many start-ups listing their shares this year, each is trying to avoid the traffic jam to get its own moment in the sun.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — When Jennifer Tejada, chief executive of PagerDuty, decided to take the software company public, she wanted to avoid this week. The stock market closes on Good Friday, and many people are on spring break. She had also feared being drowned out by a horde of other tech initial public offerings.

headline.main: Who Goes Public When? Tech Companies Maneuver to Stand Out in the Horde
headline.print_headline: Market-Bound Start-Ups Jockey to Dodge a ‘Unicorn’ Stampede

docs.lead_paragraph: Automakers, in quick succession, have moved in recent weeks to end parts of their operations in Europe. Nissan is the latest: On Tuesday, it confirmed that it would cease assembling Infiniti cars at its plant in northeast England.

docs.abstract: Carmakers say they will idle their factories to ward off supply chain problems and the police have advised retailers to increase their security.

docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Some car manufacturers will idle their factories. The police are advising store owners to hire more security guards. Trucks have been sent to the coast to practice with artificial traffic jams. And exasperated business lobbyists are warning of supply-chain calamities.

headline.main: U.K. Businesses Sound the Alarm While Planning for a No-Deal Brexit

docs.abstract: Companies and trade groups had implored British leaders to give them reassurances and information. They say they can’t wait any longer.
docs.snippet: Companies and trade groups had implored British leaders to give them reassurances and information. They say they can’t wait any longer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Businesses have been sounding the alarm over Britain’s impending departure from the European Union ever since its approval in a 2016 referendum. But this week, with lawmakers unable to agree on any sort of orderly plan as the March deadline for a deal nears, their warnings rang louder — and some decided to act.

headline.main: Businesses Are Taking Action After Brexit Warnings Go Unheeded
headline.print_headline: Businesses Take Action Amid Brexit Turmoil
